name: Brennan conjecture
summary: The Brennan conjecture is a hypothesis in complex analysis about the integral of the derivative of a conformal map. It states that for a conformal map from a simply connected planar domain to the unit disk, the integral of the absolute value of the derivative raised to a power \(p\) is finite, specifically for \(p\) between \(4/3\) and \(4\). While Brennan proved it holds for \(4/3<p<3+\delta \) for some \(\delta >0\), the conjecture remains unproven for the full range of \(4/3<p<4\).Â
head: \(W\) is a simply connected open subset of the complex plane with at least two boundary points, and \(f\) is a conformal map of \(W\) onto the open unit disk \(\mathbb{D}\)
